result.execSummary:
The defendant Frank D Curry IV was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

8:33 Defendant Frank D Curry in court with attorney Richard E Bender.  Defendant Frank D Curry in custody.  Elizabeth R Constable appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Jordan Jazdzewski is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Constable. He is an officer with the Wisconsin Rapids Police Department. On 4/19/14 he responded to a disturbance in the City of Wisconsin Rapids. When he arrived, a neighbor reported that a male and female were outside the residence arguing and the male carried the female into the residence against her will. He looked into the window of the residence and it defendant was on top of victim on the couch. He spoke to the female and she reported that she was in an argument with the defendant. she indicated the defendant struck her several times and he put his hands around her neck and it was hard for her to breathe. She then left the residence but returned with defendant before the police arrived. She stated that she hurt and requested an ambulance. The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom. Attorney Bender cross-examines witness. 
B.P. is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Bender. She states that she and defendant have been in a long-term relationship. She testifies as to what happened that night. She states that defendant did not hit her. She states she was not restrained and she was not choked. She does not remember what the argument was about. She was transported to the hospital because she had a severe headache. Attorney Constable cross-examines witness. 
Attorney Constable makes statement.
Attorney Bender makes statement.
Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed and the defendant committed it. Bound over for further proceedings. Attorney Bender requests bond be amended to signature bond and no contact order be lifted. Court amends bond to $2,000 signature bond. No contact order will remain.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for May 16, 2014 at 10:00 am.
